{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TaCruaks5tYe8G7qcJah8h","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive view of the spark-pi namespace. Let me compile the audit findings:\n\n**CORRECTLY CONFIGURED (Compliant):**\n\n1. **RBAC - Dedicated Service Account**: A dedicated `spark-pi` ServiceAccount is used (not the `default` SA), and it's properly referenced in all workloads (spark-master deployment, spark-worker deployment, and spark-pi job).\n\n2. **RBAC - Least-Privilege Role**: Role `spark-pi-role` grants only necessary verbs (`create`, `get`, `list`, `watch`, `delete`, `update`, `patch`) on limited resources (`services`, `configmaps`, `persistentvolumeclaims`). No cluster-wide permissions.\n3. **RBAC - Proper Binding**: RoleBinding `spark-pi-role-binding` correctly binds `spark-pi-role` to the `spark-pi` ServiceAccount within the namespace scope.\n\n4. **Resource Limits Set**: All three workloads (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-pi job) have explicit CPU and memory requests and limits set—CPU requests of 200m with 500m limits, and memory requests of 512Mi with 1Gi limits.\n\n5. **Pinned Image Tag**: All containers use `apache/spark:3.5.3` (explicit version tag, not `latest`).\n\n6. **Image Pull Policy**: `IfNotPresent` is set, which avoids unnecessary image pulls.\n\n7. **Job Restart Policy**: The `spark-pi` job uses `restartPolicy: Never` with `backoffLimit: 0`, which is appropriate for a single-run Spark job.\n\nNow looking at the security gaps—all three pod specs have empty `securityContext` objects at the pod level, missing critical settings like `runAsNonRoot`, explicit user/group IDs, `fsGroup`, and `seccompProfile`. Additionally, there's no container-level security context defined in any of the workloads.\n\nAt the container level, I'm seeing missing `allowPrivilegeEscalation: false`, no read-only root filesystem enforcement, no capability dropping, and `privileged` isn't explicitly set to false. There are also no `NetworkPolicy` resources, so pods can communicate freely across the cluster. The namespace lacks `LimitRange` and `ResourceQuota` definitions, meaning workloads could consume unbounded resources. The `default` ServiceAccount isn't disabled from auto-mounting tokens, and the Spark WebUI on port 8080 appears to be exposed without restrictions.\n\nThe `spark-pi` ServiceAccount doesn't explicitly disable `automountServiceAccountToken`, so all pods using it will auto-mount the API token even when unnecessary. There's no image pull secret enforcement—the public Docker Hub image is pulled without registry restrictions. I'm also noticing there's no `PodDisruptionBudget` for the Spark deployments, which could impact availability during cluster maintenance.\n\nBut wait, I need to reconsider the scope here. The task mentions that RBAC roles, resource limits, image provenance, and security contexts have already been adjusted from defaults, so I should be identifying what's been done correctly versus what's still missing. Let me reorganize my findings to distinguish between the compliant controls and the remaining gaps.\n\nThe image is pinned to a specific version rather than using `latest`, and the job is configured to prevent retry loops. However, there are significant security gaps: no SecurityContext is defined at the pod or container level to enforce non-root execution or drop unnecessary capabilities, there's no NetworkPolicy restricting traffic between pods, and namespace-level resource controls like LimitRange and ResourceQuota are absent. The `default` ServiceAccount hasn't been disabled, and the `spark-pi` ServiceAccount is auto-mounting the API token to all pods even though the workers and job don't need Kubernetes API access. Additionally, the image comes from public Docker Hub without any image pull secrets or registry admission controls in place.\n\nNow I'm documenting these findings and preparing to create a ConfigMap to address them.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":276,"cache_read_input_tokens":34564,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":276},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a994a0b4-7ae8-4cac-bd72-a3d03f2dada3","uuid":"3d468505-bcbd-4dd7-ab42-30f532f8bb42","request_id":"req_011CcMX9EjzaTmCquQdPhwmU"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TaCruaks5tYe8G7qcJah8h","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have all the data I need. Let me compile the audit findings and create the ConfigMap."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":276,"cache_read_input_tokens":34564,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":276},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a994a0b4-7ae8-4cac-bd72-a3d03f2dada3","uuid":"ae6f1ea2-a39a-4dc5-8867-bd7a7f551589","request_id":"req_011CcMX9EjzaTmCquQdPhwmU"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TaCruaks5tYe8G7qcJah8h","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01DSHxN5o6r5YiGwzG1aBHaw","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n spark-pi create configmap config-audit --from-literal=findings.txt=\"$(cat <<'FINDINGS'\nSPARK-PI NAMESPACE COMPLIANCE AUDIT\nDate: 2026-06-24\nAuditor: Automated security audit (read-only)\nNamespace: spark-pi\n\n=======================================================================\nCOMPLIANT FINDINGS (correctly configured)\n=======================================================================\n\n[PASS] RBAC-1: Dedicated ServiceAccount\n  A dedicated 'spark-pi' ServiceAccount is created and explicitly\n  referenced in all workloads (spark-master Deployment, spark-worker\n  Deployment, spark-pi Job). The default ServiceAccount is not used\n  for any workload.\n\n[PASS] RBAC-2: Least-privilege Role\n  Role 'spark-pi-role' is namespace-scoped and grants only the\n  required verbs (create, get, list, watch, delete, update, patch) on\n  a limited set of resources (services, configmaps,\n  persistentvolumeclaims). No wildcard verbs or resources. No\n  ClusterRole or ClusterRoleBinding used.\n\n[PASS] RBAC-3: Role binding scoped to namespace\n  RoleBinding 'spark-pi-role-binding' correctly binds 'spark-pi-role'\n  to the 'spark-pi' ServiceAccount within the spark-pi namespace only.\n\n[PASS] RESOURCE-1: CPU and memory requests/limits set on all containers\n  All three workloads define explicit resource requests and limits:\n    CPU     requests=200m  limits=500m\n    Memory  requests=512Mi limits=1Gi\n  This prevents unbounded resource consumption per container.\n\n[PASS] IMAGE-1: Container image pinned to an explicit version tag\n  All containers use 'apache/spark:3.5.3' — an explicit, immutable\n  version tag rather than 'latest' or a mutable floating tag. This\n  ensures reproducible deployments and prevents unintended image\n  upgrades.\n\n[PASS] JOB-1: Job configured for single-attempt execution\n  The spark-pi Job sets backoffLimit=0 and restartPolicy=Never,\n  preventing runaway retry loops on failure.\n\n=======================================================================\nGAP FINDINGS (non-compliant — remediation required)\n=======================================================================\n\n[FAIL] SC-1: No pod-level or container-level SecurityContext defined\n  All pod specs (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-pi job) have an\n  empty securityContext ({}) at both the pod and container level.\n  Missing controls:\n    - runAsNonRoot: true  (containers may run as UID 0 / root)\n    - runAsUser / runAsGroup  (no explicit non-root UID enforced)\n    - allowPrivilegeEscalation: false  (privilege escalation not blocked)\n    - capabilities.drop: [ALL]  (Linux capabilities not restricted)\n    - seccompProfile  (no seccomp profile applied)\n    - readOnlyRootFilesystem  (root filesystem is writable)\n  Risk: A compromised container running as root with full Linux\n  capabilities can escape the container or escalate on the node.\n\n[FAIL] NET-1: No NetworkPolicy defined\n  No NetworkPolicy resources exist in the namespace. All pods have\n  unrestricted ingress and egress to/from any pod or external endpoint\n  in the cluster.\n  Risk: A compromised Spark pod can freely reach other namespaces,\n  internal services, and the Kubernetes API server.\n\n[FAIL] SA-1: automountServiceAccountToken not disabled on spark-pi SA\n  The 'spark-pi' ServiceAccount does not set\n  automountServiceAccountToken: false. All pods using this SA\n  automatically mount a Kubernetes API token, including spark-worker\n  and the spark-pi job, which do not require Kubernetes API access.\n  Risk: A token exposed inside a worker container can be used to\n  authenticate to the API server if the container is compromised.\n\n[FAIL] SA-2: default ServiceAccount not disabled\n  The 'default' ServiceAccount in spark-pi exists without\n  automountServiceAccountToken: false. Any pod that omits a\n  serviceAccountName will auto-mount the default SA token.\n  Risk: Accidentally or maliciously created pods inherit API access.\n\n[FAIL] NS-1: No LimitRange or ResourceQuota at namespace level\n  No LimitRange or ResourceQuota objects exist in the namespace.\n  Without namespace-level defaults, any new pod admitted without\n  explicit resource limits can consume unbounded CPU/memory.\n  Risk: Resource exhaustion on the node; denial of service to\n  co-located workloads.\n\n[FAIL] IMAGE-2: Image sourced from public Docker Hub without registry control\n  'apache/spark:3.5.3' is pulled directly from Docker Hub with no\n  image pull secret, no admission webhook enforcing a trusted private\n  registry, and no image digest pinning (SHA256). The tag '3.5.3'\n  could theoretically be overwritten on the public registry.\n  Recommendation: mirror to an internal registry and pin by digest\n  (e.g., apache/spark@sha256:<digest>).\n\n[FAIL] NET-2: Spark Master Web UI exposed without authentication or restriction\n  The spark-master Deployment exposes port 8080 (Spark Web UI) with no\n  NetworkPolicy to restrict access. Any pod in the cluster can reach\n  the Web UI, which may expose job details, environment variables, and\n  allow job submission depending on configuration.\n\n=======================================================================\nSUMMARY\n=======================================================================\nCompliant controls : 6\nGap findings       : 7\n\nPriority remediation order:\n  1. SC-1  — Add SecurityContext (runAsNonRoot, drop capabilities,\n             allowPrivilegeEscalation: false) to all pod/container specs.\n  2. NET-1 — Create NetworkPolicy resources to restrict ingress/egress.\n  3. SA-1  — Set automountServiceAccountToken: false on spark-pi SA\n             (or per-pod for workloads that need API access).\n  4. SA-2  — Set automountServiceAccountToken: false on default SA.\n  5. NS-1  — Add LimitRange defaults and a ResourceQuota.\n  6. IMAGE-2 — Mirror image to trusted registry, pin by digest.\n  7. NET-2 — Restrict Spark Web UI access via NetworkPolicy.\n\nNo changes were made to the cluster during this audit.\nFINDINGS\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap with compliance findings"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":276,"cache_read_input_tokens":34564,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":276},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a994a0b4-7ae8-4cac-bd72-a3d03f2dada3","uuid":"b9f5fbb2-6383-4acf-bc1c-30a78889004a","request_id":"req_011CcMX9EjzaTmCquQdPhwmU"}
